var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"profile","text":"<p>I'm Alis, a DevOps engineer passionate about open-source, cloud-native technologies, and public health. I'm currently working at Skylight on projects that enable public health agencies to leverage modern, cloud-based software solutions. Feel free to follow me on GitHub or connect with me on LinkedIn.</p> <p> </p> <ul> <li> <p>Skylight Projects</p> </li> <li> <p>CDC Cloud Enablement</p> <ul> <li>Enabling public health agencies with flexible cloud hosting options so they can leverage modern, cloud-based software solutions with fewer costs and maintenance burdens.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>CDC DIBBS</p> <ul> <li>An open-source, modular toolkit designed to automate data processing, reduce manual effort, and address critical data challenges within a modern public health data infrastructure.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>CDC SimpleReport</p> <ul> <li>A free tool that makes it easy for non-traditional and under-resourced disease testing sites to record results for diagnostic tests and quickly report data to public health departments.</li> </ul> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-work","title":"\ud83d\ude80 My work","text":"<ul> <li>alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>CDCgov/terraform-aws-dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-aws</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-azure</li> <li>alismx/dibbs-cloud-tools</li> <li>alismx/DevOpsMemes</li> <li>alismx/nomad</li> <li>skylight-hq/dibbs-landing</li> <li>alismx/dibbs-ecr-viewer-playbook</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-pull-requests","title":"\ud83c\udf31 My pull requests","text":"<ul> <li>Add rds permission for database version update on CDCgov/dibbs-aws</li> <li>chore: rename NBS env vars to JWT env vars on CDCgov/terraform-aws-dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>feat: add SCA container scanning with Trivy blog post and site updates on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>feat: add SCA container scanning with Trivy blog post and site updates on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>feat: add Trivy IaC workflow and regenerate site on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>chore: update SAST IAC Checkov blog post on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>fix: correct checkov blog post wording and nav labels on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>feat: add Checkov CI workflow and SAST blog post on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>chore: regenerate site and update generated files on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>chore: update site navigation, colors, and plugins on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-gists","title":"\ud83d\udcd3 My gists","text":"<ul> <li>How to: Use qemu-img command to convert between vmdk, raw, qcow2, vdi, vhd, vhdx formats/disk images (qemu-img create, snapshot, resize etc.)</li> <li>Emulating ARM with QEMU on Debian/Ubuntu</li> <li>Debian 12 preseed file</li> <li></li> <li></li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#recent-followers","title":"\ud83d\udc6f Recent followers","text":"<ul> <li>urbantech</li> <li>trinhminhtriet</li> <li>ezgidemirci</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-certifications","title":"\ud83d\udcc8 My certifications","text":""},{"location":"index.html#microsoft","title":"Microsoft","text":"<p>Azure Fundamentals</p>"},{"location":"index.html#pluralsight-a-cloud-guru-formerly-linux-academy","title":"Pluralsight (A Cloud Guru, formerly Linux Academy)","text":"<p>Essential Container Concepts</p> <p>LPI Linux Essentials</p> <p>Kubernetes Essentials</p> <p>AWS Concepts</p> <p>AWS Essentials</p> <p>DevOps Essentials</p>"},{"location":"blog/index.html","title":"blog","text":""},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html","title":"DevSecOps: Pre-commit Hooks for Automated Checks","text":"<p>A secret committed to Git leaks to anyone with read access to the repo. Pre-commit hooks are a chance to catch those mistakes before they're written to history.</p> <p>TL;DR: Pre-commit hooks run automated checks before every <code>git commit</code>. They catch security issues before it's committed, the cheapest time to fix anything.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#why-pre-commit-hooks","title":"Why pre-commit hooks","text":"<p>After <code>git commit</code>, the code exists in the repository. After <code>git push</code>, it exists in CI. After a merge, it's on its way to production. Each step out costs more to fix than the last.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#how-pre-commit-hooks-work","title":"How pre-commit hooks work","text":"<p>A pre-commit hook is a script stored in <code>.git/hooks/pre-commit</code>. Git runs it before each commit. If the script exits with a non-zero code, the commit is blocked and the developer sees the output.</p> <pre><code>#!/bin/sh\n# .git/hooks/pre-commit\n\necho \"Running security checks...\"\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose --redact /dev/null\nif [ $? -ne 0 ]; then\n  echo \"Found a secret. Commit blocked.\"\n  exit 1\nfi\n\necho \"All checks passed.\"\n</code></pre> <p>Make it executable:</p> <pre><code>chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit\n</code></pre> <p>This is a shell script that runs whatever you want before a commit, but it's not committed to the repo. This should be used by developers to add their preferred checks on top of the team's agreed upon pre-commit framework.</p> <p>This approach is straightforward but requires developers to install all tools manually, and requires every dev to keep their hooks up to date as the project evolves.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#pre-commit-framework-recommended","title":"pre-commit framework (recommended)","text":"<p>The pre-commit framework (pre-commit.com) manages hooks declaratively and handles installation automatically (or notifies you if something isn't).</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#install","title":"Install","text":"<pre><code>pip install pre-commit\n</code></pre>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#configuration","title":"Configuration","text":"<pre><code># .pre-commit-config.yaml\nrepos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks\n    rev: v8.29.0\n    hooks:\n      - id: gitleaks\n        args: [--verbose, --redact]\n  ...\n  - repo: local\n    hooks:\n      - id: checkov\n        name: checkov\n        entry: checkov -d .\n        language: system\n        pass_filenames: false\n</code></pre> <p>Some repos like Gitleaks and Bandit have official remote hooks and can be install automatically. Checkov doesn't have an official pre-commit remote repo, so you define it as a local hook that runs the <code>checkov</code> binary directly. That also means pre-commit won't install checkov for you, so developers need to install checkov before <code>pre-commit install</code> works.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#how-it-works","title":"How it works","text":"<p>After installing with <code>pre-commit install</code>, the hooks run automatically on every commit:</p> <pre><code># Run install\npre-commit install\n</code></pre> <pre><code># Run all hooks on the entire repo\npre-commit run --all-files\n\n# Run a specific hook\npre-commit run gitleaks\n\n# Run hooks on staged files only\npre-commit run\n</code></pre> <p>The commit is blocked if any hook exits non-zero. The developer sees the output and can fix the issue.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#execution","title":"Execution","text":"<p>Gitleaks on staged files (not full history) runs fast. Bandit on staged Python files runs fast. Checkov on all IaC files in the repo takes longer because it scans the entire directory.</p> <p>If you want to avoid blocking on slow findings during quick commits, use <code>pre-commit</code>'s <code>stages</code> feature:</p> <pre><code>repos:\n  - repo: https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks\n    rev: v8.29.0\n    hooks:\n      - id: gitleaks\n        stages: [commit]\n  ...\n  - repo: local\n    hooks:\n      - id: checkov\n        name: checkov\n        entry: checkov -d .\n        language: system\n        pass_filenames: false\n        stages: [push]\n</code></pre> <p>This runs checkov only on <code>git push</code> (pre-push hook), not on every commit. Developers can commit IaC changes and push them later for the full scan. You lose the pre-commit guarantee for checkov but gain speed during active development.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#ci-is-still-a-requirement","title":"CI is still a requirement","text":"<p>CI catches things the developer missed. If someone bypasses the hook or forgets to install it, CI blocks the merge. It's not as clean because the commit has already landed, but it's better than nothing.</p>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#choose-the-tools","title":"Choose the tools","text":"<p>You don't need to run every check. Pick the ones that match what you ship with an eye for guarding secrets and keeping your systems secure.</p> <p>Consider using any of these posts for inspiration:</p> <ul> <li>Bandit: Python SAST</li> <li>Checkov: IaC SAST</li> <li>Gitleaks: Git Secret Scanning</li> <li>Trivy: Container SAST</li> </ul>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/15/devsecops-pre-commit-hooks-for-automated-checks.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>The pre-commit framework manages hooks and installation declaratively. Manual git hooks are a shell script that requires manual setup and manual tool installation.</li> <li><code>language: system</code> hooks get no virtual environment: pre-commit won't install checkov for you because it has no official remote repo. Developers must install it themselves.</li> <li>CI is a vital second line, not just a fallback. If someone bypasses the hook or forgets to install it, CI catches it later. The commit has already landed, but it's better than nothing.</li> <li>Use <code>stages: [push]</code> for slow tools to avoid blocking on quick commits during active development.</li> <li>Each tool catches a different class of mistake.</li> </ul>","tags":["pre-commit","security","git","ci","shift-left","bandit","gitleaks","checkov","sast","secrets","python","terraform","iac"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html","title":"DevSecOps: Scan Container Images with Trivy","text":"<p>Containers images ship software. They also ship vulnerabilities. Outdated base images, exposed secrets, misconfigured image instructions. Trivy scans container images for CVEs, misconfigurations, secrets, and license issues in one command.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install Trivy, scan your container images with <code>trivy image</code>, enable additional scanners, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch vulnerabilities before deployment.</p>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#install-trivy","title":"Install Trivy","text":"<pre><code># Ubuntu/Debian\nsudo apt install apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl gnupg\ncurl -fsSL https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb/public.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/trivy.gpg\necho \"deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/trivy.gpg] https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb $(lsb_release -sc) main\" | sudo tee -a /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt install trivy\n</code></pre> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>trivy --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#scan-a-container-image","title":"Scan a container image","text":"<p>Basic usage: scan a public image for vulnerabilities and secrets:</p> <pre><code>trivy image python:3.4-alpine\n</code></pre> <p>Vulnerability and secret scanning are both enabled by default. The output groups findings by OS package type, then gets into specific packages:</p> <pre><code>Report Summary\n\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502                                   Target                                   \u2502    Type    \u2502 Vulnerabilities \u2502 Secrets \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n\u2502 python:3.4-alpine (alpine 3.9.2)                                           \u2502   alpine   \u2502       37        \u2502    -    \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n...\n\npython:3.4-alpine (alpine 3.9.2)\n\nTotal: 37 (UNKNOWN: 0, LOW: 4, MEDIUM: 16, HIGH: 13, CRITICAL: 4)\n\n\u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u252c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510\n\u2502   Library    \u2502 Vulnerability  \u2502 Severity \u2502 Status \u2502 Installed Version \u2502 Fixed Version \u2502                            Title                             \u2502\n\u251c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u253c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2524\n\u2502 expat        \u2502 CVE-2018-20843 \u2502 HIGH     \u2502 fixed  \u2502 2.2.6-r0          \u2502 2.2.7-r0      \u2502 expat: large number of colons in input makes parser consume  \u2502\n\u2502              \u2502                \u2502          \u2502        \u2502                   \u2502               \u2502 high amount...                                               \u2502\n\u2502              \u2502                \u2502          \u2502        \u2502                   \u2502               \u2502 https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2018-20843                   \u2502\n...\n</code></pre> <p>To scan only vulnerabilities (disables the default secret scanner):</p> <pre><code>trivy image --scanners vuln python:3.4-alpine\n</code></pre> <p>To enable only misconfiguration or license scanning:</p> <pre><code>trivy image --scanners misconfig myapp:latest\ntrivy image --scanners license myapp:latest\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#scan-container-image-metadata","title":"Scan container image metadata","text":"<p>Container images have configuration metadata, the container image instructions that built them. Trivy can scan this configuration for misconfigurations and secrets:</p> <pre><code># Dockerfile-style misconfigurations (USER, HEALTHCHECK, ADD vs COPY)\ntrivy image --image-config-scanners misconfig myapp:latest\n\n# Secrets in environment variables (credential leaks in config)\ntrivy image --image-config-scanners secret myapp:latest\n</code></pre> <p>These are disabled by default. The misconfiguration scanner converts the image config into Dockerfile format and runs Dockerfile checks against it. The secret scanner looks for credentials in environment variables stored in the config JSON.</p>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#scan-an-image-tar-file","title":"Scan an image tar file","text":"<p>Trivy can scan images saved as tar archives. Useful for offline or CI environments:</p> <pre><code>docker pull ruby:3.1-alpine3.15\ndocker save ruby:3.1-alpine3.15 -o ruby-3.1.tar\ntrivy image --input ruby-3.1.tar\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#scan-by-architecture","title":"Scan by architecture","text":"<p>By default, Trivy scans on the host's architecture. Cross-architecture images need the <code>--platform</code> flag:</p> <pre><code>trivy image --platform=linux/arm alpine:3.16.1\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#sbom-generation-and-vulnerability-scanning","title":"SBOM generation and vulnerability scanning","text":"<p>Trivy can generate Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) for container images:</p> <pre><code># Generate SBOM in CycloneDX format\ntrivy image --format cyclonedx -o sbom.json python:3.4-alpine\n\n# Generate SBOM in SPDX format\ntrivy image --format spdx-json -o sbom.json python:3.4-alpine\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#compliance","title":"Compliance","text":"<p>The <code>docker-cis-1.6.0</code> check evaluates container image configurations against the CIS Docker Benchmark:</p> <pre><code>trivy image --compliance docker-cis-1.6.0 myapp:latest\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#authentication","title":"Authentication","text":"<p>For private registries, authenticate with:</p> <pre><code>trivy registry login --username myuser --password mypassword registry.example.com\n</code></pre> <p>Then scan as normal. Trivy reads the registry credentials before pulling the image.</p>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#filter-findings","title":"Filter findings","text":"<p>Trivy lets you narrow scans by severity:</p> <pre><code># Only HIGH and CRITICAL\ntrivy image --severity HIGH,CRITICAL alpine:3.18\n\n# Only HIGH severity\ntrivy image --severity HIGH alpine:3.18\n</code></pre>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#add-to-cicd","title":"Add to CI/CD","text":"<pre><code># .github/workflows/trivy.yml\nname: Trivy\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  trivy:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Run Trivy vulnerability scanner\n        uses: aquasecurity/trivy-action@v0.36.0\n        with:\n          image-ref: myapp:latest\n          format: table\n          exit-code: 1\n          severity: HIGH,CRITICAL\n</code></pre> <p><code>exit-code: 1</code> causes the job to fail on HIGH or CRITICAL findings. Use <code>format: sarif</code> and add the <code>upload-sarif</code> action for inline annotations.</p>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#understand-what-trivy-scans","title":"Understand what Trivy scans","text":"<p>Trivy checks four categories against files inside container images:</p> Category What it finds Enabled by default Vulnerabilities CVEs in OS packages and language dependencies Yes Misconfigurations IaC files inside the image (Kubernetes, Terraform) No Secrets Hardcoded credentials, tokens, API keys Yes Licenses Open source license compliance No","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/13/devsecops-scan-container-images-with-trivy.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Trivy scans for vulnerabilities and secrets by default. Use <code>--scanners</code> to enable misconfiguration and license scanning.</li> <li><code>--image-config-scanners</code> scans the image's configuration metadata, not the filesystem inside it.</li> <li><code>--input</code> lets you scan tar files and OCI layout directories instead of live registries. Useful for offline CI.</li> <li><code>--severity</code> and <code>--exit-code</code> control CI gating.</li> <li>Use <code>--platform</code> for multi-arch images. Trivy only scans the host architecture without it.</li> </ul>","tags":["trivy","vulnerability","container","sca","compliance","sbom","docker","kubernetes","security","oci","podman","containerd","sarif","dockerfile","misconfig","secret","license","ci","github","tar","registry","offline","cache","config","cyclonedx","spdx"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html","title":"DevSecOps: Scan for Secrets in Your Git Repository","text":"<p>Accidentally committed API keys and tokens cause breaches. Gitleaks scans Git history for these patterns.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install gitleaks, configure your repository, run a scan, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch secrets before they reach production.</p>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#install-gitleaks","title":"Install gitleaks","text":"<pre><code>sudo apt install gitleaks\n</code></pre> <p>Verify the install:</p> <pre><code>gitleaks --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#configure-gitleaks","title":"Configure gitleaks","text":"<p>Create a <code>gitleaks.toml</code> file in your repository root:</p> <pre><code>[extend]\nusing = \"github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks\"\n\n[allowlist]\ndescription = \"global allow lists\"\nregexes = [\n    # patterns to allow\n]\n</code></pre> <p>Add a custom rule:</p> <pre><code>[[rules]]\nid = \"my-custom-secret\"\ndescription = \"Custom secret pattern\"\nregex = '''(your-pattern-here)'''\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#scan-your-repository","title":"Scan Your Repository","text":"<pre><code># Full history scan\ngitleaks detect --source .\n\n# Verbose output (shows actual secrets)\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose\n\n# Verbose output (redacts actual secrets)\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose --redact\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#add-to-local-git-hooks","title":"Add to local git hooks","text":"<pre><code>#!/bin/sh\n# .git/hooks/pre-commit\n\nsudo apt install gitleaks\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose --redact /dev/null\n</code></pre> <p>Make it executable:</p> <pre><code>chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#add-gitleaks-to-cicd","title":"Add gitleaks to CI/CD","text":"<pre><code>name: gitleaks\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  scan:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v6\n        with:\n          fetch-depth: 0\n      - uses: gitleaks/gitleaks-action@v3\n        env:\n          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Scan the full Git history. People commit secrets and then delete them from current files, but the values remain in commit history.</li> <li>Use <code>--verbose</code> when investigating findings. It reveals the secret value, not just the file and line.</li> <li>Add gitleaks to your CI on pull requests. Preventing the secret from reaching production is cheaper than responding after it does.</li> </ul>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci","precommit","detect","allowlist","rule","redact"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html","title":"DevSecOps: Scan Infrastructure Code for Misconfigurations with Checkov","text":"<p>Infrastructure code contains security misconfigurations. Open buckets, unencrypted databases, overly permissive access policies. Checkov scans IaC files across 20+ formats for these patterns before you deploy.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install checkov, scan your IaC directory, configure your repository, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch infrastructure misconfigurations before they reach production.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#install-checkov","title":"Install checkov","text":"<pre><code>pip install checkov\n</code></pre> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>checkov --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#scan-a-project","title":"Scan a project","text":"<p>Basic usage: scan an entire directory recursively:</p> <pre><code>checkov -d /path/to/iac\n</code></pre> <p>Scan a single file:</p> <pre><code>checkov -f /path/to/main.tf\n</code></pre> <p>Checkov groups findings by resource type. AWS findings use <code>CKV_AWS_XX</code> IDs, Azure uses <code>CKV_AZURE_XX</code>, Kubernetes uses <code>CKV_K8S_XX</code>, and so on.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#configuration-files","title":"Configuration files","text":"<p>You can configure checkov with a YAML file in your repo:</p> <pre><code># .checkov.yaml\ncheck:\n  skip-check:\n    - CKV_AWS_21\n    - CKV_AWS_34\ncompact: true\n</code></pre> <p>The <code>skip-check</code> list matches <code>--skip-check</code> on the command line. The <code>compact</code> flag collapses findings and only displays failures.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#output-formats","title":"Output formats","text":"<p>Checkov supports several output formats. The default is text. For CI integration, use JSON, SARIF, or JUnit XML.</p> <pre><code># Default: human-readable text\ncheckov -d .\n\n# JSON (parseable in CI)\ncheckov -d . -o json -o findings.json\n\n# SARIF (GitHub Code Scanning, GitLab SAST)\ncheckov -d . -o sarif -o findings.sarif\n\n# JUnit XML (for CI systems)\ncheckov -d . -o junitxml -o findings.xml\n</code></pre> <p>SARIF integrates with GitHub Code Scanning and GitLab SAST which renders findings as in-line annotations on the source files.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#add-to-cicd","title":"Add to CI/CD","text":"<p>The <code>checkov-action</code> with the <code>github_failed_only</code> output reports failures on the GitHub action page.</p> <pre><code># .github/workflows/checkov.yml\nname: Checkov\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  checkov:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Run Checkov\n        uses: bridgecrewio/checkov-action@v12\n        with:\n          output_format: github_failed_only\n</code></pre>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#understand-the-checks","title":"Understand the checks","text":"<p>Checkov has 750+ built-in policies across 20+ IaC types.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#iac-formats","title":"IaC formats","text":"IaC Type Format Suppression Terraform / OpenTofu .tf, .tofu, .hcl, .tfvars <code># checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_21: reason</code> Kubernetes .yaml, .json <code>checkov.io/skip1: CKV_K8S_20=reason</code> CloudFormation .json, .yaml, .yml, .template <code># checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> Dockerfile Named files (Dockerfile, Dockerfile.*, dockerfile) <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_DOCKER_1: reason</code> Bicep .bicep <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AZURE_1: reason</code> ARM Templates .json CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Ansible .yaml, .yml, .json <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_ANSIBLE_1: reason</code> Argo Workflows .yaml <code>checkov.io/skip1: CKV_ARGO_1=reason</code> Serverless Framework .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> AWS SAM .yaml, .yml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> OpenAPI .yaml, .json <code>// checkov:skip=CKV_OPENAPI_1: reason</code> Azure Pipelines .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AZUREPIPELINES_1: reason</code>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#auto-detected","title":"Auto-detected","text":"<p>Helm and Kustomize auto-detect config file presence, then template out to Kubernetes manifests for scanning. AWS CDK requires running <code>cdk synth</code> to generate a CloudFormation JSON template, which checkov then scans.</p> IaC Type Format Suppression Helm Auto-detected by Chart.yaml presence Via <code>#checkov:skip</code> on templates Kustomize Auto-detected by kustomization.yaml presence Via <code>#checkov:skip</code> on templates AWS CDK Synthesized from .ts, .js, .py (cdk synth to JSON first) CDK construct metadata","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#vcs-configuration","title":"VCS configuration","text":"<p>Checkov evaluates organization and repository settings from the respective APIs, not from code files. You need to provide a personal access token for each platform.</p> IaC Type Format Suppression GitHub Actions .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_GITHUB_1: reason</code> GitHub Configuration .json (fetched from GitHub API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) GitLab CI .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_GITLABCI_1: reason</code> GitLab Configuration .json (fetched from GitLab API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Bitbucket Pipelines .yml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_CIRCLECIPIPELINES_1: reason</code> Bitbucket Configuration .json (fetched from Bitbucket API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) <p>See the GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket scan examples for required environment variables.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#other","title":"Other","text":"IaC Type Format Suppression SCA .lock, .json, .txt, .xml, .toml (varies by language) File-level comment in lock file Git History (repository commit history, not a file format) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Terraform Plan .tfplan (Terraform plan output, not source) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) <p>Checkov's full policy index is auto-generated from the source and available at Policy Index.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/12/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Use <code>--skip-check</code> or <code>.checkov.yaml</code> for known misconfigurations. Don't skip checks blindly.</li> <li>Use <code>checkov:skip</code> comments to suppress individual findings in the code. Explain why.</li> <li>SARIF output integrates with GitHub Code Scanning for inline annotations on source files.</li> <li>Run checkov in CI on pull requests. Prevent misconfigurations from reaching production.</li> </ul>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","sast","kubernetes","cloudformation","dockerfile","bicep","ansible","argoworkflows","serverlessframework","awssam","openapi","azurepipelines","helm","kustomize","awscdk","githubactions","gitlab","bitbucket","sca","sarif","git","security"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html","title":"DevSecOps: Run SAST on Python Code with Bandit","text":"<p>Insecure Python patterns (<code>eval()</code>, <code>os.system()</code>, hardcoded credentials) end up in production repos. Bandit scans Python code to find them.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install Bandit, configure your repository, run a scan, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch security issues before they reach production.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#install-bandit","title":"Install Bandit","text":"<pre><code>pip install bandit\n</code></pre> <p>The apt package is outdated at 1.6.2. Use pip for the current version (1.9.4).</p> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>bandit --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#extras","title":"Extras","text":"<p>Bandit has optional extras for additional functionality:</p> <pre><code># SARIF output formatter (for GitHub and other tools)\npip install bandit[sarif]\n\n# Baseline comparison (ignore known-vulnerabilities)\npip install bandit[baseline]\n\n# TOML configuration support\npip install bandit[toml]\n</code></pre> <p>These aren't needed to start. They become useful once you're past the basic scanning phase.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#understand-the-rule-ids","title":"Understand the rule IDs","text":"<p>Bandit uses alphanumeric rule IDs. The letter prefix groups them by category:</p> Prefix Category What it checks B1xx Assertion <code>assert</code> statements in production code B2xx Exec/eval <code>eval()</code>, <code>exec()</code>, <code>pickle</code> usage B3xx Blacklist calls Dangerous function calls (shell injection, SSL bypass) B4xx Blacklist imports Insecure imports (pickle, xml, subprocess with shell=True) B5xx Crypto Weak crypto algorithms (MD5, DES, RC4) B6xx OS <code>os.system()</code>, <code>subprocess</code> with shell=True, command injection B7xx Network SSL/TLS misconfiguration, insecure protocols <p>The most commonly skipped rules are B101 (assert statements) and B602 (os.system). Whether you skip them depends on your code. If you're running Bandit on test files or production code with assertions, they'll generate noise.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#scan-a-project","title":"Scan a project","text":"<p>Basic usage:</p> <pre><code># Single file\nbandit single_file.py\n\n# Entire directory\nbandit -r /path/to/project\n\n# Limit context lines shown in output\nbandit examples/*.py -n 3 --severity-level high\n</code></pre> <p>Skip specific rules by ID:</p> <pre><code>bandit -r . --skip B101,B602\n</code></pre> <p>Skip specific directories:</p> <pre><code>bandit -r . --exclude ./tests/\n</code></pre> <p>Scan from stdin:</p> <pre><code>cat examples/imports.py | bandit -\n</code></pre> <p>You can filter by severity or confidence level:</p> <pre><code># Medium security level\nbandit -r . -ll\n\n# High security + High confidence\nbandit -r . -lll -iii\n\n# By severity name\nbandit -r . --severity-level high\n\n# By confidence name\nbandit -r . --confidence-level high\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#output-formats","title":"Output formats","text":"<p>Bandit supports several output formats. The default is plain text. For CI integration, use JSON or SARIF.</p> <pre><code># Default: human-readable text\nbandit -r .\n\n# JSON (parseable in CI)\nbandit -r . -f json -o findings.json\n\n# SARIF (for GitHub and other tools)\nbandit -r . -f sarif -o findings.sarif\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#configuration-files","title":"Configuration files","text":"<p>You can configure Bandit with a YAML or TOML file, or an INI file called <code>.bandit</code>.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#yaml","title":"YAML","text":"<pre><code># bandit.yaml\nskips:\n  - B101\n  - B602\n\nexclude_dirs:\n  - tests\n  - migrations\n</code></pre> <pre><code>bandit -c bandit.yaml -r .\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#toml","title":"TOML","text":"<pre><code># pyproject.toml\n[tool.bandit]\nexclude_dirs = [\"tests\", \"migrations\"]\nskips = [\"B101\", \"B602\"]\n</code></pre> <pre><code>bandit -c pyproject.toml -r .\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#config-generator","title":"Config generator","text":"<p>Bandit ships <code>bandit-config-generator</code> which generates a full configuration file with all detected plugins:</p> <pre><code>bandit-config-generator -s B101,B602 -o bandit.yaml\n</code></pre> <p>This is useful for understanding what plugins are available and their default settings. Edit the output down to what your project actually needs.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#suppress-individual-findings","title":"Suppress individual findings","text":"<p>If a line triggers a finding that you've reviewed and determined is safe, add <code># nosec</code>:</p> <pre><code># This hash is for unique IDs only, not security\nthe_hash = md5(data).hexdigest() # nosec\n</code></pre> <p>The whole line gets suppressed. If you only want to suppress specific checks on that line, name them:</p> <pre><code>self.process = subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls *', shell=True)  # nosec B602, B607\n</code></pre> <p>You can use full test names instead of IDs:</p> <pre><code>assert yaml.load(\"{}\") == []  # nosec assert_used\n</code></pre> <p>Always add a comment explaining why you're suppressing the finding. Without context, future reviewers won't know if the suppression is intentional or lazy.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#baseline-ignore-known-vulnerabilities","title":"Baseline: ignore known vulnerabilities","text":"<p>If you have findings that are known and not currently actionable (e.g., a cleartext password in a unit test), generate a baseline and pass it to subsequent scans:</p> <pre><code># Generate baseline\nbandit -f json -o baseline.json -r .\n\n# Subsequent scans ignore baseline findings\nbandit -b baseline.json -f json -r .\n</code></pre> <p>This is cleaner than suppressing individual lines when you have dozens of known-vulnerabilities.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#add-to-local-git-hooks","title":"Add to local git hooks","text":"<p>Add Bandit as a pre-commit git hook:</p> <pre><code>#!/bin/sh\n# .git/hooks/pre-commit\n\npip install -q bandit\nbandit -r . -ll -f json -o /dev/null\n</code></pre> <p>Make it executable:</p> <pre><code>chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#add-to-cicd","title":"Add to CI/CD","text":"<pre><code># .github/workflows/bandit.yml\nname: Bandit SAST\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  scan:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Set up Python\n        uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n        with:\n          python-version: '3.12'\n      - name: Install Bandit\n        run: pip install bandit[sarif]\n      - name: Run Bandit\n        run: bandit -r . -f sarif -o bandit-results.sarif\n      - name: Upload SARIF\n        uses: github/codeql-action/upload-sarif@v3\n        with:\n          sarif_file: bandit-results.sarif\n</code></pre> <p>The SARIF output format integrates directly with GitHub's code scanning UI, which is nicer than trying to parse plain-text results.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Bandit catches the common things: <code>eval()</code>, <code>os.system()</code>, weak crypto, hardcoded secrets</li> <li>Use <code>--severity-level</code> and <code>--confidence-level</code> to control finding noise</li> <li><code># nosec</code> suppresses a line. Name the specific checks if you only want to suppress certain ones</li> <li>Baseline files are cleaner than suppressing individual findings for known-vulnerabilities</li> <li>SARIF output integrates with GitHub code scanning</li> <li>Local git hooks catch findings before they reach CI</li> <li>The apt version is stale. Use pip for the current rule set.</li> <li>Always explain why when you skip a rule or add a <code># nosec</code> comment</li> </ul>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci","sarif","pre-commit","baseline","yaml","toml","rule","severity","confidence"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html","title":"DevSecOps: Manage Terraform Versions with tfenv","text":"<p>State file incompatibility between Terraform versions breaks your pipelines. tfenv manages multiple versions so you can pin a specific version, switch between them, and keep CI aligned with your local environment.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install tfenv, switch to the version your project needs, and pin it in CI to prevent version drift between local and remote environments.</p>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","opentofu","version","github","ci","git","pin","shell","semver"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#install-tfenv","title":"Install tfenv","text":"<pre><code>git clone https://github.com/tfutils/tfenv.git ~/.tfenv\n</code></pre> <p>Add it to your shell profile:</p> <pre><code># ~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc, etc.\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.tfenv/bin:$PATH\"\n</code></pre> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>tfenv --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","opentofu","version","github","ci","git","pin","shell","semver"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#check-available-versions","title":"Check available versions","text":"<pre><code># All available versions\ntfenv list-remote\n\n# Filter for a specific major version (1)\ntfenv list-remote | grep \"^1\\.\"\n</code></pre> <p>Terraform uses semantic versioning: breaking changes only happen between major versions. Minor and patch updates are compatible with existing state.</p>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","opentofu","version","github","ci","git","pin","shell","semver"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#switch-versions","title":"Switch versions","text":"<pre><code># Install a specific version\ntfenv install 1.15.0\n\n# List installed versions\ntfenv list\n\n# Switch to a version\ntfenv use 1.15.0\n\n# Write current version to .terraform-version\ntfenv pin\n</code></pre> <p>This file is tracked in git. Anyone who runs <code>tfenv use</code> (or <code>terraform</code> with tfenv installed) will use the pinned version.</p> <pre><code># Reads from .terraform-version by default\ntfenv use\n</code></pre>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","opentofu","version","github","ci","git","pin","shell","semver"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li><code>.terraform-version</code> is tracked in git, so the whole team uses the same Terraform version. This is the source of truth.</li> <li><code>tfenv use</code> reads from <code>.terraform-version</code> by default. <code>tfenv pin</code> writes to it. The primary workflow is both without arguments.</li> <li>Terraform uses semantic versioning: breaking changes only happen between major versions. Minor and patch updates are safe.</li> </ul>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","opentofu","version","github","ci","git","pin","shell","semver"]}]}